---
// src/pages/cane-toad-dog-poisoning/index.astro
// Targets: "cane toad dog symptoms" (500/mo)
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import ContentImage from '../../components/ContentImage.astro';
import dogsToadSafety from '../../assets/images/dogs-dog-toad-safety.png';
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Cane Toad Dog Poisoning: Symptoms and Emergency Response Guide"
  description="Cane toad dog poisoning symptoms can escalate in minutes. Learn exactly what to do immediately, when to go to an emergency vet, and how South Florida owners can prevent future exposures."
>

  <div class="urgency">
    <strong>⚠️ Emergency:</strong> If your dog mouthed or licked a cane toad, begin rinsing the mouth now and head to an emergency vet immediately.
  </div>

  <div class="hero">
    <h1>Cane Toad Dog Poisoning: What to Do Right Now</h1>
    <p>Cane toad toxin can cause life-threatening poisoning in dogs within minutes. This guide gives you a fast, step-by-step emergency response protocol, key symptoms to watch for, and prevention steps for South Florida homes.</p>
    <a href="#emergency-steps" class="btn btn-lg">Jump to Emergency Steps →</a>
  </div>

  <div class="lead-form-wrap" id="get-quote">
    <h2>Get Connected with a Local Removal Provider</h2>
    <p>Already seeing toads around your home? Enter your zip code and we'll match you with a licensed local professional.</p>
    <iframe data-tally-src="https://tally.so/embed/0QL69P?alignLeft=1&hideTitle=1&transparentBackground=1&dynamicHeight=1" width="100%" height="320" frameborder="0" marginheight="0" marginwidth="0" title="Homeowner Request Form"></iframe>
  </div>

  <div class="content">

    <h2 id="immediate-risk">How Dangerous Is Cane Toad Poisoning for Dogs?</h2>
    <p>Cane toads (also called bufo toads) secrete a potent toxin from glands behind their shoulders. When a dog bites, licks, or mouths the toad, toxin is absorbed through the gums and oral tissues very quickly.</p>
    <p>Severe cases can progress from drooling and disorientation to seizures and heart complications in as little as 15 minutes. Fast action is critical: immediate rinsing plus urgent veterinary care gives your dog the best chance of recovery.</p>

    <figure class="content-figure">
      <ContentImage
        src={dogsToadSafety}
        alt="Dog near a cane toad outdoors — pets can be poisoned quickly if they mouth or lick invasive bufo toads in Florida"
      />
      <figcaption>Keep dogs supervised at night in cane toad territory; even brief contact with toxin can be an emergency.</figcaption>
    </figure>

    <h2 id="emergency-steps">Emergency Steps: What To Do Immediately</h2>
    <ol>
      <li><strong>Stay calm and act fast.</strong> Move your dog away from the toad and prevent further contact.</li>
      <li><strong>Rinse the mouth for 10-15 minutes.</strong> Use a hose or sink sprayer and flush from the side of the mouth outward.</li>
      <li><strong>Keep water out of the throat.</strong> Point the muzzle slightly downward so water and toxin flow out, not back.</li>
      <li><strong>Wipe gums and tongue as you rinse.</strong> Use a wet cloth to remove sticky toxin residue.</li>
      <li><strong>Go to an emergency veterinarian now.</strong> Do not wait for symptoms to worsen before leaving.</li>
      <li><strong>Call ahead while in transit.</strong> Tell the clinic you suspect cane toad poisoning so they can prepare.</li>
    </ol>

    <h3>What Not To Do</h3>
    <ul>
      <li>Do not induce vomiting unless instructed by a veterinarian.</li>
      <li>Do not give food, treats, or oral medications first.</li>
      <li>Do not delay care to "watch and wait" after rinsing.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2 id="symptoms">Common Cane Toad Poisoning Symptoms in Dogs</h2>
    <p>Symptoms often begin quickly and can escalate rapidly. Watch for:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>Excessive drooling or foaming at the mouth</li>
      <li>Pawing at the mouth, gagging, or head shaking</li>
      <li>Bright red gums</li>
      <li>Vomiting or diarrhea</li>
      <li>Staggering, disorientation, or collapse</li>
      <li>Muscle tremors or seizures</li>
      <li>Rapid, irregular, or labored breathing</li>
    </ul>
    <p>Even if symptoms appear mild at first, get veterinary care right away. Early treatment can prevent severe progression.</p>

    <h2 id="vet-care">What the Emergency Vet Will Typically Do</h2>
    <p>Treatment depends on severity but usually focuses on stabilizing the nervous and cardiovascular systems while reducing toxin effects. The veterinary team may monitor heart rhythm, treat tremors or seizures, provide IV support, and manage body temperature.</p>
    <p>Bring a short timeline of what happened (time of exposure, first symptoms, and what rinsing was done). This helps the team move faster.</p>

    <h2 id="prevention">How To Prevent Future Encounters</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Leash and supervise at night:</strong> Most encounters happen after dark when toads are active.</li>
      <li><strong>Remove pet food and water bowls overnight:</strong> These attract insects and toads.</li>
      <li><strong>Reduce outdoor lighting where possible:</strong> Less insect activity means fewer toads.</li>
      <li><strong>Eliminate standing water:</strong> Empty plant saucers and fix low spots where water collects.</li>
      <li><strong>Do a quick yard scan before potty breaks:</strong> Focus on pool edges, shrub lines, and damp corners.</li>
    </ul>
    <p>Already seeing toads regularly? <a href="/cane-toad-removal/">Connect with a removal pro →</a></p>

    <h2 id="south-florida-context">Why This Is a Major South Florida Risk</h2>
    <p>Cane toads are established across Miami-Dade, Broward, Palm Beach, Collier, and Lee counties. Warm nights, irrigation, pools, and suburban landscaping create ideal habitat, which is why pet exposures are common in the region.</p>
    <p>For broader context on identification, habitat, and long-term control, see our pillar guide: <a href="/cane-toad-florida/">Cane Toads in Florida →</a></p>

    <h2 id="faq">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
    <div class="faq">
      <details>
        <summary>How quickly can cane toad poisoning affect a dog?</summary>
        <p>Symptoms can begin within minutes. In severe exposures, life-threatening complications can develop in as little as 15 minutes, which is why immediate rinsing and emergency vet care are both essential.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>Is mouth rinsing enough by itself?</summary>
        <p>No. Rinsing is critical first aid, but it does not replace emergency veterinary treatment. Always head to a vet immediately after rinsing.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>Are small dogs at higher risk?</summary>
        <p>Yes. Smaller dogs often have less physiological reserve and may deteriorate faster, but dogs of any size can have severe reactions.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>Are cane toads and bufo toads the same thing?</summary>
        <p>Yes. "Bufo toad" is a common nickname for the cane toad. In South Florida, both names refer to the same invasive species.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>What's the best way to reduce risk at home?</summary>
        <p>Night-time supervision, yard habitat reduction, and professional removal when toads are recurring is the most reliable strategy. <a href="/cane-toad-removal/">Find a local removal provider →</a></p>
      </details>
    </div>

    <p><strong>Already seeing toads?</strong> <a href="/cane-toad-removal/">Connect with a removal pro →</a></p>

  </div>

</BaseLayout>
